Every time I speak in front of an audience, whatever I say, social media slander follows calling for my candidacy as a member of parliament to be rejected in the next elections, exposing the centre's politics and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments to my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who face a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but do not allow themselves to be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this age of politics is that severe slander is apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church, and with every “moment of distrust” or change of selection rules, the party becomes more petty.
Over the past two years, I have often been advised to keep my head low, not just to express my opinion loudly and then I would ‘not get in trouble’.
But I didn't go into politics for that.
Since I joined Labour as a schoolchild 32 years ago, provoked by the neglect of the Thatcher government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a councillor and in my role as a minister.
I have never kept my politics hidden, not even in the last elections.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy stances and my arguments with the current leadership.
To those who advocated the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country drags on to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my voters, whether they are members of Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats of rejecting my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not stop me from acting according to what I believe is in your best interest.
Chris Leslie is Member of Parliament for Nottingham East.
