'The sea is ours': land-locked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rigging naval office in La Paz.
Public buildings are covered with an ocean blue flag.
On all naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: “The sea is ours.
It is a duty to win them back.”
In all of Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that the country had to give to Chile after a bloody nineteenth-century commodity conflict is still alive, as is the desire to re-enter the Pacific Ocean.
That hope may have reached its highest point in recent decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice, which should fall on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course looks forward to the result with positive prospects,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the court’s ruling on big screens, hoping that the Hague court will advocate in favor of Bolivia that Chile, after decades of intense talks, is obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Also for Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is facing a controversial fight for re-election next year, there is a lot at stake with Monday’s ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he swore at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no authority to allocate the Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s ruling falls only six months after the final hearings indicates that the case was “not complicated,” says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And the prospects of a positive outcome for Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, the situation may have worsened in the past four years.
“The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government,” Zárate said.
The warlike rhetoric of Morales has completely undermined all the goodwill that Chile may have still had, she claimed.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to continue afterwards.
The two countries have not had an ambassador to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court’s decision was taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will have “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of international relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, uses the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific,” he added.
“The statement is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind.”
