North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions lead to increasing mistrust in the United States and that under such circumstances, the country would in no way be able to unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site for nuclear tests, and pledging not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any trust in the US, there will be no trust in our national security and under such circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves.”
Although Ri repeated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded as it takes further steps, it was striking that he did not disapprove of unilateral denuclearization a priori, as Pyongyang used to do.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is striving for a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. is urging ‘denuclearization first’ and increasing the pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an aerial castle of the people who are ignorant about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only strengthen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the US leader suggested earlier this week at the United Nations.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such an impasse.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles were aimed at the U.S. mainland so after ‘Mr. Evil President’ Trump called Kim a ‘missile man’ on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim this year at the United Nations for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much still needs to be done and that sanctions must continue until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timetable for this: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the sanctions of the Security Council must be continued vigorously and firmly until we have realized the full, definitive, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to significantly reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo had a meeting with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit meeting.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea pledged to dismantle a rocket site and a nuclear complex if the United States took “correspondent measures” during a meeting with Moon this month.
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he wanted were security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor noted that the students of the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, drafted the course. As far as he knows, it is unique in the US.
He was given the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, organised for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, the students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we find that they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what effects the choice of cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in studying at night still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who is studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler set up the course because he had been teaching with the professor last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive setting.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm before their bedtime, not just an alarm to get up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, causing you to have trouble falling asleep.
