Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the almanac of our 'Sunday Morning': September 30, 1882, today exactly 136 years ago, for who can tell... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm 'Hans' Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then, the geiger counter has become an icon in pop culture, for example in Bells or Coronado, a 1950 film starring the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: “What the hell is that?”
Rogers: ‘That’s a Geiger counter, which is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: “It’s really popping up right now!”
'Hans' Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach the Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Immune System to ‘See’ and Kill Malignant Cells
Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Malignant Cells in Treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells in a patient to modify them in a lab
They can then “see” a protein that is common in many types of cancer and are then re-injected.
A test vaccine delivers promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months
In the method, immune cells are removed in a patient, after which the cells in the lab are adjusted in such a way that they can ‘see’ the protein HER2, which is common in all types of cancer, and then the cells are re-injected.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results show that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “stimulates the growth of various types of cancer,” including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer, and colon cancer, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar way of removing immune cells from patients and ‘learning’ these cells to tackle cancer cells has been found to work in the treatment of a certain type of leukemia.
