What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed to reducing poverty?
This Saturday the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York, an annual music event where a very impressive line-up of stars will perform and that has an equally impressive mission: the end of poverty in the world.
For the seventh time, tens of thousands of people will come to the Great Lawn in Central Park for the Global Citizen Festival. Not only to enjoy acts like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes but also to raise awareness for the real purpose: ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was first organized in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international advocates who hope to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
Concertgoers who want to get a free ticket to the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket) had to complete a series of tasks, or "actions," such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or in any other meaningful way raising awareness for the goal: an end to poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with 12 years left to go to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a suitable way to convince people to demand a call to action or is this just another form of ‘clicktivism’, making people feel that they are making a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen, more than 19 million ‘actions’ of supporters have been registered, targeting a wide range of different targets.
According to Global Citizen, these actions have helped global leaders engage and make policy proposals worth more than $37 billion that should change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or collected through sponsorship actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of UK investors and executives aimed at “helping children realize their full potential,” has pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the UK government, donors, other national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can turn the social injustice that is malnutrition into a footnote in history,” Tracey Ullman, ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, told the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that, after sending more than 5,000 actions asking the UK government to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced support for a project, the Power of Nutrition, that will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional interventions.
In response to one of the most frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen website asking "why do you think we can end extreme poverty?"
the group replied, "It will be a long and difficult road, where we will sometimes fall and fail.
But, just like the civil rights and anti-apartheid movements ahead of us, we will ultimately be successful because we are stronger together.
Janet Jackson, The Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monáe are some of the artists who will perform at this year’s New York event presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
