National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the ordinary and the small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
Employees of the NTS and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat’s cries and which species does what.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to create a detailed image of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as creating meadows and how best to maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, just like flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not blind in reality.
However, their nightly hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, sleep inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats, and that’s why the work we do here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He emphasizes the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the potentially unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially eradicating a complete local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and from many of our species, we simply don’t know how their populations are.”
