“When I was a kid, I saw Scotland play in Hampden Park with my father and it’s something that keeps attracting me.
But that would only come if I succeeded in managing a club.”
The predecessors of Ross as managers of Sunderland include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
Former Alloa Athletic boss says he was not intimidated to become the successor to these established names at a large club, having previously refused advances from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me at this moment is measured by 'can I let this club return to the Premier League?'
Because of the structure and facilities of this club, it should undoubtedly be in the Premier League," he said.
"It is not an easy task to achieve this, but I can only see myself as successful when I bring the club back there."
Ross is only three years into his career as a manager, after a period as an assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months in the coaching group of Hearts.
He then helped Alloa recover from third division degradation and transformed St Mirren from on the verge of degradation to winning the Championship in the following season.
Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever did during his career as a footballer at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was probably really a crossroads," he recalled from the moment he took over the lead at Alloa.
“I really believed that the management was the right choice for me, much more than playing.
