Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of Central Celebes Province and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Celebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when the tsunami struck.
Donggala is a regency that extends over 300 km along the coast of northwest Celebes.
The regency, an administrative region just below a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main activities in the economy of the Central Celebes province, particularly in the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but they are mostly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been regularly hit by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to the Agency for Combating Disasters of Indonesia.
In 1938, a tsunami claimed more than 200 lives and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck west of Donggala in 1996, with nine deaths.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Fire and is often hit by earthquakes.
Here is a list of some of the most severe earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh on north Sumatra on December 26 caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries and claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the coasts of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of major earthquakes took place on the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people were killed on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake on the Richter scale occurred south of Java, Indonesia’s most densely populated island, causing a tsunami that struck the southern coast and claimed nearly 700 lives.
2009: An earthquake of magnitude 7.6 on the Richter scale struck the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of 7.5 on the Richter scale struck one of the Mentawai Islands off the coast of Sumatra, causing a tsunami of more than 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and claimed around 300 human lives.
2016: A shallow earthquake hit the regency of Pidie in Aceh and caused destruction and panic as people were reminded of the devastation of the 2004 deadly earthquake and tsunami.
There was no tsunami this time, but more than 100 people were killed by falling buildings.
2018: Several earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and caused thousands of tourists to be stranded temporarily.
