Red glow update: Concentrations decrease in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decline in red glow concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, fragmentary increases in red glow are reported in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decline in concentrations.
The Red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots to be seen, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported off the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are ongoing reports of respiratory irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwest Florida, there was no report of airway irritation in the past week.
